example.p:
Consider the linear transformation $\ltdefn{T}{\complex{3}}{M_{22}}$ defined by

\lt{T}{\colvector{a\\b\\c}}=\begin{bmatrix}
a-b&2a+2b+c\\3a+b+c&-2a-6b-2c
\end{bmatrix}

How would we define $\lt{S}{B}$?

\lt{S}{B}&=\lt{S}{\lt{T}{\colvector{1\\-2\\4}}}
=\lt{\left(\compose{S}{T}\right)}{\colvector{1\\-2\\4}}
=\lt{I_{\complex{3}}}{\colvector{1\\-2\\4}}=\colvector{1\\-2\\4}
or
\lt{S}{B}&=\lt{S}{\lt{T}{\colvector{0\\-3\\8}}}
=\lt{\left(\compose{S}{T}\right)}{\colvector{0\\-3\\8}}
=\lt{I_{\complex{3}}}{\colvector{0\\-3\\8}}=\colvector{0\\-3\\8}

Now choose either of the two inputs used above for $T$ and add to it a scalar multiple of the basis vector for the kernel of $T$.  For example,

\vect{x}=\colvector{1\\-2\\4}+(-2)\colvector{-1\\-1\\4}=\colvector{3\\0\\-4}

then verify that $\lt{T}{\vect{x}}=B$.  Practice creating a few more inputs for $T$ that would be sent to $B$, and see why it is hopeless to think that we could ever provide a reasonable definition for $\lt{S}{B}$!  There is a whole subspace's worth of values that $\lt{S}{B}$ would have to take on.

proof.p:
Now check the second defining property of a linear transformation for $\ltinverse{T}$,

\lt{\ltinverse{T}}{\alpha\vect{x}}&=
\lt{\ltinverse{T}}{\alpha\lt{T}{\lt{\ltinverse{T}}{\vect{x}}}}
&&\\
&=\lt{\ltinverse{T}}{\lt{T}{\alpha\lt{\ltinverse{T}}{\vect{x}}}}
&&\\
&=\alpha\lt{\ltinverse{T}}{\vect{x}}
&&

Choose $\vect{u}\in U$.  Define $\vect{v}=\lt{T}{\vect{u}}$.  Then $\preimage{T}{\vect{v}}=\set{\vect{u}}$, so that $\lt{S}{\vect{v}}=\vect{u}$ and,

\lt{\left(\compose{S}{T}\right)}{\vect{u}}
=\lt{S}{\lt{T}{\vect{u}}}
=\lt{S}{\vect{v}}
=\vect{u}
=\lt{I_U}{\vect{u}}

and since our choice of $\vect{u}$ was arbitrary we have function equality, $\compose{S}{T}=I_U$.

Now choose $\vect{v}\in V$.  Define $\vect{u}$ to be the single vector in the set $\preimage{T}{\vect{v}}$, in other words, $\vect{u}=\lt{S}{\vect{v}}$.  Then $\lt{T}{\vect{u}}=\vect{v}$, so

\lt{\left(\compose{T}{S}\right)}{\vect{v}}
=\lt{T}{\lt{S}{\vect{v}}}
=\lt{T}{\vect{u}}
=\vect{v}
=\lt{I_V}{\vect{v}}

and since our choice of $\vect{v}$ was arbitrary we have function equality, $\compose{T}{S}=I_V$.

subsection.p:
When a linear transformation is both injective and surjective, the pre-image of any element of the codomain is a set of size one (a singleton).  This fact allowed us to construct the inverse linear transformation in one half of the proof of  (see ) and is illustrated in the following cartoon.  This should remind you of the very general  which was used to illustrate  about pre-images, only now we have an invertible linear transformation which is therefore surjective and injective ().  As a surjective linear transformation, there are no vectors depicted in the codomain, $V$, that have empty pre-images.  More importantly, as an injective linear transformation, the kernel is trivial (), so each pre-image is a single vector.  This makes it possible to turn around all the arrows to create the inverse linear transformation $\ltinverse{T}$.

